<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,583,1231,1257]" box="[151,583,1231,1257]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,583,1231,1257]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" reason="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Desmarest" authorityName="Desmarest" box="[151,583,1231,1257]" class="Mammalia" family="Echimyidae" genus="Makalata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="didelphoides">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,583,1231,1257]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,424,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Makalata didelphoides</emphasis>
(Desmarest)
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,1302,1976]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,320,1302,1327]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Identification.</emphasis>
This arboreal spiny rat has a distinct reddish orange nose and small rounded ears covered by thin hairs. The dorsal pelage is yellowish brown streaked with black, the fur is a mixture of thin bristles and stiff spines with orangish yellow tips; ventral pelage is pale orange with a mixture of gray hairs. The tail is shorter than the head and body length, furred up to 
<quantity box="[552,674,1410,1434]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" unit="mm" value="25.0" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="20.0">20–30 mm</quantity>
from the base with orange hairs and covered by small light yellow hairs. 
<collectingCountry box="[219,275,1446,1470]" name="India" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Hind</collectingCountry>
feet are short and broad, bearing strong claws.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,1302,1976]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Craniodental characters (
<figureCitation box="[481,564,1482,1506]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="27.[151,250,723,746]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,176,710]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[226,1360,162,710]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 16. Dorsal, ventral and lateral views of skull and mandible of Makalata didelphoides (male, UFES 1387)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/206290/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Fig. 
<number box="[535,564,1482,1506]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
) agree with the diagnosis given by Patton 
<emphasis box="[1053,1104,1483,1507]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">et al</emphasis>
. (
<number box="[1127,1189,1482,1506]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="2000.0">2000</number>
). The rostrum is relatively short and broader anteriorly; the interorbital region is broad, convergent anteriorly, and has supraorbital crests that extend onto parietals. The incisive foramen is small and flanked by small ridges that extend to the narrow palate. The mesopterygoid fossa extends to the posterior half of M 
<number box="[957,972,1590,1614]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="2.0">2</number>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Emmons" box="[983,1165,1590,1614]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" refString="Emmons, L. H. (1993) On the identity of Echimys didelphoides Desmarest, 1817 (Mammalia: Rodentia: Echimyidae). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 106, 1 - 4." type="journal article" year="1993">
Emmons (
<number box="[1099,1157,1590,1614]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="1993.0">1993</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
reported that tooth-fold pattern varies within and between populations of 
<taxonomicName box="[723,906,1627,1651]" class="Mammalia" family="Echimyidae" genus="Makalata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="didelphoides">
<emphasis box="[723,906,1627,1651]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">M. didelphoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Specimens collected along the mid-Araguaia River have three folds opening labially, isolating four lophs. The second fold on every cheek-teeth entirely connects both labial and lingual sides.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
